This essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive. While the piece is sponsored, these ar=
e all my real and genuine views. I=E2=80=99m writing fewer Sponsored Deep D=
ives, because as I said when I wrote about LayerZero in December, I=E2=80=
=99m only writing them on companies that I think have a chance to be really=
 important in an area I care about. You can read more about how I choose wh=
ich companies to do deep dives on, and how I write them here [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/2fa0efd9-f6fa-4a86-9554-08ce5d2543e3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Clear Street clears that bar: making the capital markets (and capitalism) r=
un more efficiently and effectively is one of the most important things the=
re is, and the full-stack Hard Startup approach its taking is full of lesso=
ns for founders who want to build insanely ambitious things in the face of =
incredibly deep-pocketed incumbents.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Clear Street: From COBOL to the Cloud [ https://substack.com/redirect/1dad3=
9d4-537b-4321-8bc3-ecd62a8e9ab1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
It=E2=80=99s easy to tell when physical infrastructure decays.=C2=A0
You can see the rust on the bridges, feel the bump of the pothole, experien=
ce the terror of trice-daily train derailments [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/2d989606-f207-451a-9c9b-4df983fd7a71?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], fill your cup with brownish water from =
the sink, and open your social media app of choice to discover how a Boeing=
 737 Max fell apart this time.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s hard to fix physical infrastructure because people use it ever=
y day. Shutting down a bridge means a minor inconvenience for thousands of =
people, so we put it off and risk major catastrophe.
It=E2=80=99s harder to tell when digital infrastructure decays.=C2=A0
Digital infrastructure is invisible, the pipes that power an ever-increasin=
g amount of our lives, how we communicate, work, get around, and transact. =
It=E2=80=99s easy to forget that digital infrastructure is there because us=
ually, it just works.=C2=A0
Like physical infrastructure, digital infrastructure is hard to fix because=
 people use it everyday. It=E2=80=99s also hard because once companies reap=
 the rewards of building the digital infrastructure on top of which other c=
ompanies build, no one inside of those companies is incentivized to fix it.=
=C2=A0
Building infrastructure that others build on is a long journey with a huge =
payoff: the switching costs of replacing infrastructure are high. If given =
the choice between risking the cash cow to make the infrastructure better a=
nd just letting it slowly degrade while the cash cow produces, most infrast=
ructure providers will choose the latter, to their own short-term benefit b=
ut to the long-term detriment of the whole system.
This is the reason banks still run on Common Business-Oriented Language, mo=
re commonly known as COBOL, a 65-year-old programming language that pretty =
much only 65-year-olds (and older) [ https://substack.com/redirect/f434314f=
-ec2a-4a11-aa84-cfcc0c453f65?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] know how to maintain.=C2=A0
Over $3 trillion flows through COBOL every day. For decades, layers upon la=
yers of disparate coding languages and technologies have been built on top =
of this infrastructure. And for a whole host of reasons, banks don=E2=80=99=
t rip it out and replace it.=C2=A0
Doing so would introduce the kind of short-term risks that come with tinker=
ing with something built by someone who=E2=80=99s long-since retired and he=
ld together by a patchwork of digital duct tape. Not doing so, however, int=
roduces the kind of major risk that threatens the financial markets and the=
 invisible, counterfactual risk that comes from not innovating.=C2=A0
With physical infrastructure, you can=E2=80=99t just delete all of the road=
s and start fresh. The roads are the roads, and we need to fix what we got =
a little at a time, like after a bridge collapses on I-95 [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/91f4143b-a6d7-41fb-a7fb-5a64010b4e8c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
With digital infrastructure, you can start fresh. It=E2=80=99s just really =
hard. It requires a combination of capital, experience, technical sophistic=
ation, and a different way of viewing risk.=C2=A0
Clear Street [ https://substack.com/redirect/a599ccd8-3b03-4dc1-8f1b-dbe5db=
083fb9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 is doing it. In the early stages of a long journey, there are signs that i=
t=E2=80=99s working. The cloud-native prime brokerage company recently clos=
ed a $250 million extension to a previous round, bringing that round=E2=80=
=99s total to $685 million at a $2.2 billion post-money valuation. It has $=
750 million on its balance sheet =E2=80=93 a necessity in the prime brokera=
ge business =E2=80=93 and generated $260 million in revenue in 2023, its fi=
fth year of business. Oh, and it=E2=80=99s EBITDA profitable.=C2=A0
The $2.2 billion valuation seems hefty for a five-year-old company, but rel=
ative to the opportunity, it=E2=80=99s small. Companies that have chewed of=
f just the easier, surface-level piece of the problem =E2=80=93 better inte=
rfaces on old infrastructure =E2=80=93 like Broadridge and Interactive Brok=
ers - are worth $24 billion and $41 billion in the public markets, respecti=
vely. Banks like Goldman, Morgan Stanley, Citi, JP Morgan, and Bank of Amer=
ica are worth, collectively, over $1 trillion.=C2=A0
Clear Street believes that the banks are going to have a very difficult tim=
e modernizing their own systems while running them simultaneously and poten=
tially putting the trillions at risk. This isn=E2=80=99t just speculation: =
Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s demise can be traced to poor risk management stemmi=
ng from bad infrastructure.=C2=A0
The banks=E2=80=99 reticence is Clear Street=E2=80=99s opportunity: to rebu=
ild the infrastructure from the outside, and replace the old system with th=
e new, slowly at first, one client, geography, and asset at a time, until f=
inancial markets around the world eventually run on Clear Street.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
Tackling that opportunity means building a startup in a different way than =
most startups build. This isn=E2=80=99t a story of minimum viable products =
and pivots. Because it=E2=80=99s building infrastructure, Clear Street look=
s more like the Techno-Industrials [ https://substack.com/redirect/70160141=
-c3e2-415f-a205-e969b1e2a5b0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that operate against a clear roadmap, with higher ca=
pital requirements and more specialized talent, from day one, than like a t=
raditional software company.=C2=A0
Clear Street=E2=80=99s cofounder, Uri Cohen, started the business with his =
own capital in 2018 after experiencing the pain, and worrying about the ris=
k of trading on crumbling infrastructure for over two decades on Wall Stree=
t. He recruited a CEO, Chris Pento, and a CTO, Sachin Kumar to co-found the=
 company, both of whom had felt the same pain.=C2=A0
Then, in 2020, they bought their own online brokerage, CenterPoint Securiti=
es, to serve as the first customer of Clear Street=E2=80=99s clearing, cust=
ody, and prime brokerage products. If they were going to ask financial inst=
itutions to move off of their old, but tried and true, infrastructure, they=
=E2=80=99d need to prove that it worked on themselves, a la Amazon=E2=80=99=
s first and best customer strategy [ https://substack.com/redirect/815c8ac1=
-e827-4271-bd66-1ae6ddeff0ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0=C2=A0
Meanwhile, they got to work completely rebuilding financial infrastructure =
from the ground up with modern software that needs to communicate with anti=
quated systems, like DTCC, and a hodgepodge of customers=E2=80=99 bespoke p=
atchworks of code. They also began building all of the things that a prime =
brokerage needs to do to win clients=E2=80=99 business: research, investmen=
t banking, capital introductions, securities lending, margin, and more all =
at the same time.=C2=A0
Clear Street, while still early in its journey, is executing on its mission=
 to build the cloud native pipes through which the capital markets will one=
 day run, across every major asset class, in every major market, replacing =
the antiquated system that everyone from small prime brokerages to large ba=
nks use to move trillions of dollars every day.=C2=A0
And they=E2=80=99re offering a diverse product set that takes advantage of =
this modern technology stack, giving the largest hedge funds that currently=
 work with banks, down to the smallest day traders that the bank can=E2=80=
=99t touch due to their cost structure, clean data from one single source o=
f truth, bringing crystal clarity into their risk, and driving operational =
and strategic efficiencies in their businesses that could lead to growth th=
at they can only currently dream of.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The ambition seems unlimited, because practically, it is. =E2=80=9CThe mark=
ets=E2=80=9D are the world=E2=80=99s largest market.=C2=A0
The risk of capital market participants not modernizing their infrastructur=
e, product offerings, and services, Uri believes, is equally huge: a Boeing=
esque series of increasingly frequent blowups like the ones that killed Arc=
hegos Capital Management, Credit Suisse, and Signature Bank, and worse.=C2=
=A0
There are a couple of ways they might come to appreciate the risk: the thre=
at and the opportunity.=C2=A0
The threat is the risk of catastrophe that comes from operating on old infr=
astructure, the risk that Credit Suisse and Signature Bank learned the hard=
 way but that takes at least a decade to remedy, at which point it=E2=80=99=
s someone else=E2=80=99s problem (or glory).=C2=A0
The opportunity is the set of possibilities that opens up when you can buil=
d products on one cloud-based platform with clean, real-time data. Every ba=
nk C-suite is thinking through how to take advantage of AI, for example, wh=
ich could be catastrophic with bad data but nirvanic with good data.=C2=A0
In either case, the banking industry has proven that words aren=E2=80=99t a=
s powerful as incentives. The industry=E2=80=99s current leaders don=E2=80=
=99t want to wade through the quagmire of replacing infrastructure, so Clea=
r Street needs to build new infrastructure in parallel so that adopting it =
is a no-brainer for the industry=E2=80=99s future leaders.=C2=A0
Thinking in Risk
Clear Street was born from a lifetime of experience and one specific conver=
sation.=C2=A0
Uri has spent over two decades in the financial markets. He=E2=80=99s a co-=
founder of Alpine Global Management, a firm with a breadth of sophisticated=
 trading strategies across global markets, the kind of firm that demands a =
lot from its infrastructure.=C2=A0
A few years ago, Alpine had an issue with one of its large prime brokers, t=
he one-stop-shops investment banks and financial institutions offer to supp=
ort large investors. Prime brokers offer margin, securities lending, custod=
y, trade clearing and settlement, risk management, reporting and more. But =
this large prime=E2=80=99s risk management and reporting were broken.=C2=A0
Their system was cobbled together from a string of acquisitions, and it was=
 giving Uri the wrong data and costing him money. They miscalculated how mu=
ch equity he had, against which they provided margin, and as a result, the =
fees he was paying were wrong.=C2=A0
He needed it fixed, but there was a problem: the only guy who knew how to f=
ix it was a retired 70-year-old named Neil Stepanich who happened to be vac=
ationing in the Himalayas.=C2=A0
Uri somehow got in touch with Neil, who said that he could fix it, =E2=80=
=9Cbut it=E2=80=99s going to cost you a lot of money: $2,000.=E2=80=9D That=
 was just fine. Two hours later, it was fixed, temporarily, at least.=C2=A0
Over the next few years, Uri kept having more and more issues with the syst=
ems his prime brokers provided. He kept thinking, =E2=80=9COK, the banks wi=
ll have to fix it now,=E2=80=9D and the banks kept not fixing it.=C2=A0
Five years later, things had only gotten worse.=C2=A0
That year, in a meeting with two heads of prime brokerages, he asked, =E2=
=80=9CWhy aren=E2=80=99t you guys fixing this?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The answer was simple and human: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s going to take seven =
to ten years, a lot of money, and a lot of headaches. We=E2=80=99re not eve=
n sure we will succeed.=E2=80=9D
From their perspective, the decision not to fix makes sense: the payoff was=
 too far out and uncertain. From Uri=E2=80=99s, it didn=E2=80=99t work: the=
 system was causing him to lose money.
During that conversation, Uri made the realization that many entrepreneurs =
make at some point: if he wanted the system fixed, he was going to have to =
fix it himself.=C2=A0
Why Clear Street is So Hard to Build
What Uri, Chris Pento, and Sachin Kumar set out to build in 2018, on the su=
rface, doesn=E2=80=99t sound too dissimilar from many software startups.=C2=
=A0
Clear Street was going to take an antiquated system and modernize it with s=
oftware. Instead of mainframes, Clear Street would be cloud native. Instead=
 of clunky integrations, Clear Street would be API-first [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/1563b853-fc53-4be6-9ce=
7-dce7d0c25ef8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. In place of slow, duct-taped =
systems and manual spreadsheets, Clear Street would give clients a comprehe=
nsive view of their portfolios in real-time and the ability to execute trad=
es at internet speed.=C2=A0
And that is what they=E2=80=99re building. Clear Street offers clearing and=
 custody, execution, prime financing, and white-glove services like capital=
 introductions and account management to financial institutions and active =
traders.=C2=A0
Executing the startup playbook on the world=E2=80=99s financial infrastruct=
ure, though, is hard. Clear Street is a Hard Startup. In The Good Thing Abo=
ut Hard Things [ https://substack.com/redirect/c4c4dc66-5d33-4bd0-b7c8-c250=
a7224880?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ], I defined Hard Startups as:
The ones with no playbook, the ones that have R&D risk or some other hair o=
n them that keeps competition at bay and gives them a clear path to short-t=
erm sales and long-term defensibility if they get a great product to market=
=2E
I broke them down to bits and atoms, and included infrastructure in the bit=
s category: =E2=80=9Cthese companies are often 100x harder below the surfac=
e than above it; there=E2=80=99s a lot of schlep.=E2=80=9D
Clear Street is perhaps the best example of a bits infrastructure Hard Star=
tup I=E2=80=99ve come across. Rebuilding the world=E2=80=99s financial infr=
astructure has more hair on it than Sasquatch.=C2=A0
The software challenge is incredibly hairy in its own right, and software i=
s only one part of the story. Clear Street needs capital, risk management, =
and the client services muscle of an investment bank in order to get big cl=
ients to even use the software in the first place.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s start with the software. It=E2=80=99s the core of the busines=
s and the thing that makes Clear Street different from other prime brokerag=
es.=C2=A0
Jon Daplyn [ https://substack.com/redirect/4de9ca5b-3c63-4b63-8f82-5ec5b15c=
1a9e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
the former Head of Prime Brokerage Technology at Morgan Stanley and now Cle=
ar Street=E2=80=99s Chief Information Officer, explained the challenge.=C2=
=A0
=E2=80=9CThe hardest thing,=E2=80=9D he told me, =E2=80=9Cis that the syste=
ms you=E2=80=99re interacting with were built decades and decades ago. No o=
ne is building them; they were built in the past. You=E2=80=99ve effectivel=
y got to go and learn them from scratch.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
He described a steep learning curve and a ton of tech that needed to be bui=
lt in order to put in even the first trade.
To start, you need to build your own core books and records that keep track=
 of client information, account balances and positions, cost basis, margin =
details, and more, a big database of client information that updates in rea=
l-time. A database sounds relatively straightforward, but with so much info=
rmation, from a variety of sources, including up-to-date market data, it=E2=
=80=99s a beast.=C2=A0
When I asked Jon for an example of something that was particularly hard to =
build, he cited this =E2=80=9Caccount master,=E2=80=9D the core system that=
 maintains all client information and positions.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99d think implementing an account master would be straig=
htforward,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cbut we=E2=80=99re already rolling out=
 the second version because we didn=E2=80=99t get it quite right the first =
time.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
He noted, though, that this is the advantage of being a fintech instead of =
a bank: instead of saying =E2=80=9CWhy did you make that mistake?=E2=80=9D =
they looked at it and said, =E2=80=9CThat didn=E2=80=99t work, let=E2=80=99=
s rip it up and do it again.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9COur core value is technology, so we need it to be excellent.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0
Step one is building excellent technology internally =E2=80=93 that single =
source of truth that provides clean data to Clear Street and its clients. F=
rom there, Clear Street needs to connect its own systems with a patchwork o=
f external ones that have no willingness to change the way they work to spe=
ak with a new entrant.=C2=A0
To enable even the first trade, Clear Street=E2=80=99s systems need to comm=
unicate with an alphabet soup of organizations, each of which have their ow=
n antiquated and mission-critical systems, like DTCC (Depository Trust & Cl=
earing Corporation) and ICE (Intercontinental Exchange). The DTCC is respon=
sible for clearing US securities, but individual exchanges, like NASDAQ, ha=
ve their own clearing processes and systems that occur alongside the DTCC=
=E2=80=99s centralized clearing.
Just taking NASDAQ, trading activity on that exchange generates data that n=
eeds to flow through to post-trade systems for proper clearing and settleme=
nt. That includes obvious things like trade details =E2=80=93 how many shar=
es, what price, etc=E2=80=A6 =E2=80=93 and less obvious things, like accoun=
ting for the exchange=E2=80=99s fees. Then there are the periodic things th=
at happen =E2=80=93 like stock splits, dividends, and repurchases =E2=80=93=
 that happen at the exchange level and must get reflected properly in Clear=
 Street=E2=80=99s own systems.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s just one exchange! Clear Street needs to send data to NASDAQ=
, other exchanges, clearinghouses, and regulators in formats in which they =
can digest it, and take data back in whichever format they choose to send i=
t, clean it all up, and show it accurately in its own internal systems in o=
rder to give clients a real-time understanding of their positions, and in o=
rder to give Clear Street itself the data it needs to do things like extend=
 margin to clients without blowing itself up.=C2=A0
And then, it needs to share that data with clients in a format that works f=
or them. Many hedge funds and brokerages have built their own patchwork of =
systems and ways of handling data on top of old infrastructure, and since t=
hey=E2=80=99re not going to rip everything out and replace it with Clear St=
reet whole cloth on day one, Clear Street needs to translate the data in it=
s own system into language that each of those systems understands. It=E2=80=
=99s like a real-time Rosetta Stone operating inside of the chaos of the To=
wer of Babel.=C2=A0
And that=E2=80=99s just US equities!=C2=A0
Then, with the core systems built, Clear Street has to scale all of that =
=E2=80=93 to more clients, more assets, and more geographies, each with its=
 own idiosyncrasies and old systems with which to integrate.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s say they wanted to support bonds, or =E2=80=9Cfixed income,=
=E2=80=9D in the US. They=E2=80=99d have to integrate with the DTCC=E2=80=
=99s FICC system (Fixed Income Clearing Corporation), Fedwire, TradeWeb, an=
d the fixed income exchanges, among other systems. Internally, they=E2=80=
=99d need to update their systems to account for securities that don=E2=80=
=99t trade like equities and come with their own valuation math. I still ge=
t nightmares from reading Frank Fabozzi=E2=80=99s The Handbook of Fixed Inc=
ome Securities [ https://substack.com/redirect/2dddd153-b440-4abd-85e5-70f6=
812fd93f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] early in my career. Clear Street essentially has to incorporate the bond=
 math from that 1840 page tome into its internal systems in order to proper=
ly account for risk.=C2=A0
And then there are options (hello OCC!) and futures and all sorts of exotic=
 derivatives, some of which trade on exchanges and many of which trade over=
-the-counter (OTC) in bespoke deals. Those need to be reflected in the syst=
em, too, if Clear Street is to maintain a clear picture of its clients=E2=
=80=99 risk.=C2=A0
And if you want to add new geographies? Well, then you need to rebuild all =
of these integrations with the equivalent agencies and exchanges in each co=
untry you plan to service, each of which have their own regulations and idi=
osyncrasies. Some of these countries=E2=80=99 systems run on COBOL; others =
are more modern and run on Java and SQL. Whatever language they speak, you =
must too.=C2=A0
No one gives you bonus points for managing all of this extra complexity; th=
ey just expect it to work, to show up as a set of clear numbers that client=
s can use to trade and manage their own risk.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s no wonder that banks have no desire to rebuild all of this; if=
 it works well enough, the distant-seeming threat of catastrophe pales in c=
omparison to the clear and present schlep of having to redo all of that.=C2=
=A0
Simply put: Clear Street itself builds modern software, but that software h=
as to speak to legacy technology in whichever way partners and clients requ=
ire.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe DTCC (Depository Trust & Clearing Corporation) isn=E2=80=99t g=
oing to change their protocols for us,=E2=80=9D Jon explained. =E2=80=9CWe =
need to adapt to the way they like to speak. Then clients [like hedge funds=
] also have their own ways of speaking that you need to adapt to. Our clien=
ts say =E2=80=98This is how we talk,=E2=80=99 and if we want to do business=
 with them, we need to learn to talk that way.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I have some personal experience here. At Breather, some of the buildings we=
 were in used building access systems like Kastle that ran on old software.=
 To give our customers access to their spaces in those buildings, we had to=
 get them past security, which meant getting their names in the security sy=
stem. Which meant we had to integrate with the building access systems.=C2=
=A0
Something so seemingly simple turned out to be brutal. Integration with eac=
h new system took months of our developers=E2=80=99 time, and whichever bac=
kend developers were unlucky enough to be put on those projects absolutely =
hated it. And that was just to get some names in a database.=C2=A0
Multiplying that by hundreds of systems and adding the zero-room-for-error =
nature of handling money is a mind-numbingly complex and painful challenge =
to contemplate.=C2=A0
But if Clear Street wants to replace the world=E2=80=99s financial infrastr=
ucture with modern software, that=E2=80=99s where they have to start. Becau=
se the world=E2=80=99s financial infrastructure runs on COBOL, the people w=
ho know how to build on COBOL are getting old, and the banks aren=E2=80=99t=
 incentivized to fix the problem themselves.=C2=A0
COBOL Cowgirl, Cowboys, and Cow-Paced Banks
There are two themes that we should unpack a little further before continui=
ng the Clear Street tale.=C2=A0
First, we need to understand COBOL, the brilliant and long-lived software t=
hat still underpins so many of our systems, why it is that pretty much only=
 70-year-olds like Neil Stepanich know how to fix it, and what kind of risk=
 that represents.=C2=A0
Then, we need to dive deeper into the incentives that keep the banks on the=
ir cobbled-together COBOL despite the risks.=C2=A0
COBOL Cowgirl and Cowboys
Even the people betting their career on replacing COBOL are in awe of it.=
=C2=A0
When I asked what he thought about the language, Jon Daplyn warned me that =
he was about to recite me a love letter to COBOL.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIf you think about it,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9CSomeone wrote a =
piece of software decades ago that=E2=80=99s still working today. That=E2=
=80=99s remarkable.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
COBOL is truly remarkable.=C2=A0
In the 1940s and 1950s, computer scientists had to speak the language of ma=
chines, which they did at first by setting switches and plugging and unplug=
ging cables=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Or by feeding punch cards with data and code into machines and getting punc=
h cards with results back out=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Grace Hopper, a lieutenant junior grade in the US Navy, first worked on suc=
h a machine in 1944, when she was assigned to work with Howard Aiken=E2=80=
=99s Bureau of Ordinance Computation Project at Harvard University to work =
on the Mark II, the successor of the computer in the image above. Five year=
s later, in 1949, she joined the Eckert-Mauchly Computer Corporation as a s=
enior mathematician to work on the UNIVAC I, which would become America=E2=
=80=99s first commercially available electronic computer.=C2=A0
While working with UNIVAC, Hopper realized that the way humans programmed m=
achines =E2=80=93 not just speaking their language, but speaking a differen=
t language for each machine =E2=80=93 could be improved. She thought that h=
umans should be able to speak English to machines, or more specifically, to=
 use English-like syntax to program computers.=C2=A0
Hopper =E2=80=9Cwas told very quickly that I couldn=E2=80=99t do this becau=
se computers didn=E2=80=99t understand English. Nobody believed computers c=
ould understand anything but arithmetic.=E2=80=9D She disagreed, or rather,=
 she recognized that for computers to understand English, they=E2=80=99d ne=
ed a translator.=C2=A0
In 1952, Hopper and her team created the first compiler, a program that tra=
nslates high-level programming language code into machine language code tha=
t a computer's processor can execute. Then she developed one of the first E=
nglish-syntax programming languages, FLOW-MATIC, specifically to program th=
e UNIVAC, in 1955.=C2=A0
While Hopper was developing better ways to speak to computers, others were =
designing better computers themselves. In addition to the UNIVAC, IBM built=
 its 700/7000 Series, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) released the PDP-=
1, and National Cash Register (NCR) offered the NCR 315.=C2=A0
Recognizing the need for software that worked across all of the various har=
dware systems,=C2=A0 a committee formed by the Department of Defense and th=
e private sector proposed the idea for a common business language. In 1959,=
 it established the Conference on Data Systems Languages (CODASYL) to devel=
op that language.=C2=A0
Hopper was on the committee. Drawing on her work, CODASYL proposed a readab=
le, English-like language that could be adopted by businesses for data proc=
essing tasks. In 1960, it completed the first version of the Common Busines=
s-Oriented Language, or COBOL.=C2=A0
COBOL was a hit. It worked on mainframes from IBM, UNIVAC, Honeywell, Burro=
ughs, and Control Data Corporation (CDC), each of which provided its own co=
mpiler to translate the machine-independent COBOL into machine code specifi=
c to their machines.=C2=A0
IBM=E2=80=99s System/360, which I wrote about in Internet Computers [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/e2fd870c-fda2-44c0-aeab-1c30827a8232?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and which IBM devel=
oped for $48 billion in today=E2=80=99s dollars, took the business world by=
 storm. As Computerworld=E2=80=99s Frank Hayes explained [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/fe364d81-c53c-4c5e-b14=
2-8e8647d2c566?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CHardware compatibili=
ty meant platform stability. That led to application longevity, which made =
complexity possible. A whole new world opened up for IT, a world of huge, b=
usiness-changing megaprojects.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Many of those business-changing megaprojects took place inside of large ban=
ks, programmed in COBOL.=C2=A0
In Internet Computers, that=E2=80=99s where I left the mainframe era and mo=
ved on to the Next Big Thing: personal computers. The banks, however, and m=
any other large institutions, from insurance companies to government agenci=
es, never left.=C2=A0
More than 60 years later, 44 of the top 50 banks [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/f0faf2bf-f5bb-4f3b-871b-40cff82cec9f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and all 10 of the largest insurers, ar=
e still using mainframes programmed in COBOL.=C2=A0
That, as Jon said, is remarkable, and deserving of a love letter.=C2=A0
COBOL is reliable and efficient. Its fixed-format syntax optimizes code gen=
eration. =E2=80=9CRigorous syntax and error-checking capabilities have help=
ed COBOL programs withstand multiple updates and adaptations without endang=
ering system integrity and run relentlessly for decades.=E2=80=9D Did a mai=
nframe engineering services firm write that? Yes. [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/f0faf2bf-f5bb-4f3b-871b-40cff82cec9f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] But it seems to be true. COBOL progra=
ms are as Lindy as computer programs get.=C2=A0
But there are a couple of challenges with continuing to rely on COBOL.=C2=
=A0
The first is a straightforward one: we=E2=80=99ve developed much better way=
s to write and run software. No one starting from scratch builds on COBOL.=
=C2=A0
The second is the bigger risk: the people who know how to work with COBOL a=
re leaving the workforce.=C2=A0
When I wrote about Hadrian [ https://substack.com/redirect/94dcaece-69e7-4e=
bc-bb4d-97b7e511f191?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I wrote about a huge problem facing the precision manufactu=
ring industry: the average machinist is in their mid-50s, the average preci=
sion parts shop owner is in their 60s, and the younger generation isn=E2=80=
=99t joining the business.=C2=A0
The same thing is happening here. The average COBOL programmer is in their =
40s or 50s, and the younger generation isn=E2=80=99t backfilling them.=C2=
=A0
It=E2=80=99s no wonder. One Hacker News commenter [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/38ce1354-49ba-4b23-8c7e-fac1f4090de2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] compared learning COBOL to =E2=80=9Cs=
wallowing a barbed cube shaped pill,=E2=80=9D but cheerfully pointed out th=
at that=E2=80=99s not the hard part.=C2=A0
Even worse, the ones who really know how things work, like Neil Stepanich, =
are even older and no longer in the workforce. Reuters begins a great 2017 =
piece on the =E2=80=9CCOBOL Cowboys=E2=80=9D [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/100af537-12b8-49e1-88f0-b20db6446ae1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] by writing, =E2=80=9CBill Hinshaw is not a=
 typical 75-year-old. He divides his time between his family =E2=80=93 he h=
as 32 grandchildren and great-grandchildren =E2=80=93 and helping U.S. comp=
anies avert crippling computer meltdowns.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Hinshaw and his wife founded a company called COBOL Cowboys [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/4cfcf33a-4150-48fe-84d7-100ba62521c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], named after the movie Spac=
e Cowboys in which retired Air Force pilots are brought in to troubleshoot =
a problem in space that only they know how to solve.=C2=A0
The challenge, according to Hinshaw, is even though some young people still=
 learn COBOL, there are some things you just can=E2=80=99t teach: =E2=80=9C=
COBOL-based systems vary widely and original programmers rarely wrote handb=
ooks, making trouble-shooting difficult for others.=E2=80=9D
Only people who were there when the systems were built know how it all fits=
 together, and worse, that dwindling group of people won=E2=80=99t be aroun=
d forever.
Accenture=E2=80=99s Andrew Starrs put it bluntly. The risk is =E2=80=9Cnot =
so much that an individual may have retired," he says, but that "he may hav=
e expired, so there is no option to get him or her to come back."
What happens when the COBOL Cowboys ride into that eternal sunset?=C2=A0
There will be no one left who knows how the infrastructure on which trillio=
ns of dollars daily all fits together, no one to fix it when its inevitable=
 crumble accelerates. COBOL is incredibly impressive infrastructure, but ev=
en the best infrastructure is no match for time.=C2=A0
So why aren=E2=80=99t the banks getting ahead of the problem and doing what=
ever they can to avoid catastrophic risk?=C2=A0
Cow-Paced Banks
The short answer is that replacing the COBOL-based systems while the bank r=
uns on them is slow, expensive, and introduces short-term risks.=C2=A0
Chris Pento [ https://substack.com/redirect/508b1a11-942b-4199-8e22-9365298=
9de2d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 Clear Street=E2=80=99s CEO and co-founder, has spent his career in operati=
ons at financial institutions, from large established investment banks like=
 Merrill Lynch to startup broker dealers like Exos Financial. If anyone fee=
ls the brunt of bad systems, it=E2=80=99s the operations people who are res=
ponsible for cleaning up their mess every day.=C2=A0
I asked Chris why a big bank couldn=E2=80=99t just throw a bunch of money a=
t the problem. He told me they probably could build new systems, before lis=
ting off a litany of reasons they wouldn=E2=80=99t:=C2=A0
Building the system while running a company with diverse needs =E2=80=93 in=
cluding keeping clients happy on a daily basis =E2=80=93 adds complexity=C2=
=A0
Technical debt has built up in these systems over 30 to 40 years as people =
patch problems=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s all these connection points =E2=80=93 internally and with e=
xternal systems =E2=80=93 that have to be unconnected and reconnected, =E2=
=80=9Cand it takes five years just to figure out what the connections are.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Then, midway through the process, someone on the risk team says, =E2=80=9CH=
ey, you forgot about this=E2=80=9D and shuts the project down.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou drive on the BQE (Brooklyn-Queens Expressway),=E2=80=9D he sai=
d. =E2=80=9CYou know how bad decade-long projects can get.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The complexity and time to build it is hard and long, fraught with risk. Re=
call the patchwork of integrations we talked about earlier, integrations wi=
th the DTCC, OCC, exchanges, and regulators, in countries around the world =
and on a variety of computer systems. Like a game of Operation, touching an=
y one of them the wrong way might mean game over, so you have to go very sl=
owly and very carefully, all while protecting the core.=C2=A0
Jon Daplyn, who was responsible for these systems at Morgan Stanley, echoed=
 Chris=E2=80=99 assessment and added a technical lens. To Jon, the issue is=
 that, while the banks have tried to improve their systems, they=E2=80=99ve=
 only gotten so far because they=E2=80=99re afraid to touch the core and br=
eak the whole thing.=C2=A0
What you=E2=80=99d have to do is take a small piece of functionality from t=
he core, pull it out and rebuild it, and then bridge it back in until the c=
ore gets smaller and smaller. Thousands of people have been building and pa=
tching and patching, never really changing the core because they=E2=80=99re=
 too scared. Pulling it apart will take decades of consistent effort.
Decades may as well be millennia from the perspective of the people running=
 the banks today: they would need to foot the bill under their watch for a =
payoff that might come long after they=E2=80=99ve sailed into retirement. S=
o they take the hidden but pernicious risk that comes with inaction.=C2=A0
What Happens When the Infrastructure Breaks?=C2=A0
The big risk in the old system is that the different people who need to see=
 the same data, don=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
Do you have a single source of truth? Is there one place where your firm ca=
lculates the value of an option or many? Do your finance team, risk team, a=
nd the client all see the same values or do they see different values? Do t=
hey see the same thing eventually, or in real-time?
Sometimes, bad infrastructure shows up as potholes. Slower transactions, ex=
tra work for the back office, miscalculated fees like Uri dealt with. Annoy=
ing and inefficient, but not the end of the world.=C2=A0
Other times, it rears its head in the financial equivalent of a bridge coll=
apsing with drivers on it.=C2=A0
Like when Archegos Capital Management blew up and took Credit Suisse down w=
ith it.=C2=A0
Remember this one?=C2=A0
In March 2021, ViacomCBS sold some stock and its stock tanked. That was bad=
 news for Archegos, Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s $10 billion family office, which w=
as turbo long swaps on ViacomCBS and a number of other tech stocks on margi=
n extended by the fund=E2=80=99s prime brokers. As the prices fell, the pri=
me brokers demanded more collateral.=C2=A0
When Archegos failed to meet its margin call, its prime brokers =E2=80=93 i=
ncluding Credit Suisse, Nomura, Goldman Sachs, and Morgan Stanley, among ot=
hers =E2=80=93 raced to sell off Archegos=E2=80=99 collateral and recoup th=
eir money, crushing the prices of the assets they all held.=C2=A0
Archegos collapsed, of course, and it brought some, but not all, of its pri=
me brokers with it. As The Trade News  [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a93=
4a21-dad2-4583-95eb-e8dc4647cafb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]reported [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a934a21=
-dad2-4583-95eb-e8dc4647cafb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], speed made all the difference. And speed depended o=
n risk management systems.=C2=A0
When Archegos blew up, Goldman had the intel within seconds, Morgan Stanley=
 hesitated but sold on the same day, and Credit Suisse, which was still on =
antiquated risk management systems, waited days to catastrophic effect.=C2=
=A0
Goldman was the first to sell. Over the course of the day on March 26th, =
=E2=80=9CGoldman Sachs sold $10 billion of shares in stocks linked to Arche=
gos.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe have robust risk management that governs the amount of financin=
g we provide for these types of portfolios,=E2=80=9D said David Solomon, CE=
O of Goldman Sachs, on the bank=E2=80=99s first quarter 2021 earnings call.=
 =E2=80=9CWe identified the risk early and took prompt action consistent wi=
th the terms of our contract with the client.=E2=80=9D
Morgan Stanley was almost as quick, dumping $8 billion that same day. The f=
irm lost $911 million between money owed by Archegos and trading losses. A =
mere scratch.=C2=A0
Nomura wasn=E2=80=99t as lucky. It lost $2.87 billion in the winddown.
But the biggest loser was Credit Suisse. The Swiss bank was the slowest to =
appreciate and unwind its exposure to Archegos, and lost a nauseating $5.5 =
billion. It had to raise $1.9 billion to stay afloat, and fired both its in=
vestment bank CEO Brian Chin and, tellingly, its Chief Risk and Compliance =
Officer, Lara Werner.=C2=A0
It wasn=E2=80=99t enough. Two years later, in March 2023, the Swiss Governm=
ent and Swiss Financial Market Supervisory Authority organized the $3.2 bil=
lion fire sale of Credit Suisse to its Swiss Rival, UBS.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CCredit Suisse would be here today,=E2=80=9D Uri told me, =E2=80=9C=
if they=E2=80=99d had the right tech in place.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Or take Signature Bank.=C2=A0
The same month that UBS acquired Credit Suisse, March 2023, Signature Bank =
faced a bank run as depositors raced to withdraw their funds on the heels o=
f the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank.=C2=A0
As the FDIC went to work to assess the damage, they asked all of the at-ris=
k banks for tallies of the wires they had going out.=C2=A0
Signature Bank said, essentially, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re actually not sure =
because of our systems.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0
The FDIC said, essentially, =E2=80=9CAre you kidding me?=E2=80=9D and told =
the New York State Department of Financial Services to take possession of t=
he bank that Sunday.=C2=A0
The bank=E2=80=99s exposure to crypto was blamed in the press, but as the F=
DIC wrote in its report, =E2=80=9CSBNY management was sometimes slow to res=
pond to FDIC=E2=80=99s supervisory concerns and did not prioritize appropri=
ate risk management practices and internal controls. Management was describ=
ed by FDIC supervisors as reactive, rather than proactive, in addressing ba=
nk risks and supervisory concerns.=E2=80=9D
The real challenge that affected these firms is a lack of clean data.=C2=A0
At the surface level, that sounds like a silly and trivial-to-fix problem g=
iven the stakes. But as we=E2=80=99ve learned, for international firms that=
 handle every asset class, getting clean data means integrating hundreds of=
 systems, all which speak different languages, into one central database th=
at can translate all of that disparate data into clear metrics as fast as d=
igitally possible. When that database is built in a 70-year-old programming=
 language that few people alive truly understand, and when it needs to tran=
slate from exchanges, clearing houses, and clients that each speak their ow=
n language, the problem becomes prohibitively complex.=C2=A0
Little inconsistencies compound on each other, and as they do, the risks co=
mpound, too, until=E2=80=A6 KABOOM.=C2=A0
These are the kind of risks that Uri thinks are going to come due more and =
more frequently if the infrastructure isn=E2=80=99t fixed from the core out=
=2E=C2=A0
Fixing the infrastructure from the inside =E2=80=93 rebuilding the roads wh=
ile people are driving on them =E2=80=93 doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be an opti=
on. If it were, Clear Street wouldn=E2=80=99t exist.=C2=A0
Rebuilding the infrastructure from the ground up is hard, but it might actu=
ally be the easiest way to make sure it happens. That=E2=80=99s Clear Stree=
t=E2=80=99s bet.=C2=A0
What Clear Street is Building
A long time horizon is a competitive advantage, one that requires capital, =
vision, and the right blend of patience and momentum.=C2=A0
When I wrote about Anduril [ https://substack.com/redirect/afcd7979-8344-40=
d1-91b1-504c93a125cf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I said that it was in a goldilocks position when it came to=
 acquiring advanced technology companies: =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s well-funded=
 enough that it can make meaningful acquisitions, but privately held enough=
 that it doesn=E2=80=99t need to justify its investments in the same way pu=
blic companies do.=E2=80=9D
Clear Street sits in its own goldilocks zone: it=E2=80=99s well-funded and =
experienced enough that it can build new infrastructure with the patience i=
t requires, but fresh enough that it=E2=80=99s not constrained by the same =
demands and risks as the banks.=C2=A0
Clear Street=E2=80=99s mission is to build a modern, single source-of-truth=
 platform capable of handling every asset class, in every investor, and in =
any currency.
But that=E2=80=99s not something you can build from day one. Uri started th=
e company to solve his own pain point, but even he doesn=E2=80=99t do most =
of his trading on Clear Street yet.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CAlpine is 95% at other clearing firms,=E2=80=9D he readily admitte=
d.=C2=A0
The goal is, over time, to win more and more of Alpine=E2=80=99s business, =
and by extension, to be able to serve an increasing share of other firms=E2=
=80=99 trading business, from the very small to the very big.=C2=A0
That means building bulletproof core infrastructure, and then racing to bui=
ld new products to handle more assets in more geographies on top of the inf=
rastructure.=C2=A0
So what=E2=80=99s in the core?=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CClearing, settlement, and the bookkeeping ledger,=E2=80=9D Jon tol=
d me, =E2=80=9CThose are the things that we=E2=80=99ll protect completely.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Trading a security like a stock or bond seems simple. You just hit a button=
 in Robinhood, and voila! But there=E2=80=99s a lot that goes on behind the=
 scenes to make the trade happen, which can be broken into three steps for =
simplicity:
Execution. Someone wants to sell at a certain price, someone else wants to =
buy at that price. They=E2=80=99re matched through an order book (or automa=
ted market maker in crypto). The price is locked in. This is the front-end,=
 what you see when you trade.=C2=A0
Clearing. After the trade is executed, the details are verified and the obl=
igations of both parties =E2=80=93 one makes a payment, the other delivers =
securities =E2=80=93 are established.
Settlement. Finally, the securities and money trade hands. How and when tha=
t happens depends on the type of securities traded and the markets they tra=
de in. Stock markets are typically =E2=80=9CT+2,=E2=80=9D meaning that they=
 settle two days after execution.=C2=A0=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve ever bought or sold a stock before, you know that you don=
=E2=80=99t need to meet the person on the other side of the trade somewhere=
, hand them cash, and receive a stock certificate. The role of clearing and=
 settlement software is to orchestrate everything that needs to happen behi=
nd the scenes, including interacting with all of the intermediaries that to=
uch a transaction, like the DTCC.=C2=A0
