: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>It&#8217;s hard to fix physical infrastructure because people use it every=
 day. Shutting down a bridge means a minor inconvenience for thousands of p=
eople, so we put it off and risk major catastrophe.</p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It=
&#8217;s harder to tell when digital infrastructure decays.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">Digital infrastructure is invisible, the pipes that power an ev=
er-increasing amount of our lives, how we communicate, work, get around, an=
d transact. It&#8217;s easy to forget that digital infrastructure is there =
because usually, it just works.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Like physical in=
frastructure, digital infrastructure is hard to fix because people use it e=
veryday. It&#8217;s also hard because once companies reap the rewards of bu=
ilding the digital infrastructure on top of which other companies build, no=
 one inside of those companies is incentivized to fix it.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Building infrastructure that others build on is a long journey wi=
th a huge payoff: the switching costs of replacing infrastructure are high.=
 If given the choice between risking the cash cow to make the infrastructur=
e better and just letting it slowly degrade while the cash cow produces, mo=
st infrastructure providers will choose the latter, to their own short-term=
 benefit but to the long-term detriment of the whole system.</p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;"><span>This is the reason banks still run on Common Business-Oriented=
 Language, more commonly known as COBOL, a 65-year-old programming language=
 that pretty much only </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f434=
314f-ec2a-4a11-aa84-cfcc0c453f65?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decorat=
ion: underline;">65-year-olds (and older)</a><span> know how to maintain.&#=
160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Over </span><strong>$3 trillion flow=
s through COBOL every day</strong><span>. For decades, layers upon layers o=
f disparate coding languages and technologies have been built on top of thi=
s infrastructure. And for a whole host of reasons, banks don&#8217;t rip it=
 out and replace it.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Doing so would=
 introduce the kind of short-term risks that come with tinkering with somet=
hing built by someone who&#8217;s long-since retired and held together by a=
 patchwork of digital duct tape. Not doing so, however, introduces the kind=
 of major risk that threatens the financial markets and the invisible, coun=
terfactual risk that comes from </span><em>not </em><span>innovating.&#160;=
</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>With physical infrastructure, you can&#8=
217;t just delete all of the roads and start fresh. The roads are the roads=
, and we need to fix what we got a little at a time, like after a </span><a=
 href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/91f4143b-a6d7-41fb-a7fb-5a64010b4e8c=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">bridge collapse=
s on I-95</a><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>With digital infrast=
ructure, you </span><em>can </em><span>start fresh. It&#8217;s just really =
</span><strong>hard</strong><span>. It requires a combination of capital, e=
xperience, technical sophistication, and a different way of viewing risk.&#=
160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/re=
direct/a599ccd8-3b03-4dc1-8f1b-dbe5db083fb9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); t=
ext-decoration: underline;">Clear Street</a></strong><span> is doing it. In=
 the early stages of a long journey, there are signs that it&#8217;s workin=
g. The </span><strong>cloud-native prime brokerage </strong><span>company r=
ecently closed a $250 million extension to a previous round, bringing that =
round&#8217;s total to $685 million at a </span><strong>$2.2 billion post-m=
oney valuation.</strong><span> It has $750 million on its balance sheet &#8=
211; a necessity in the prime brokerage business &#8211; and generated $260=
 million in revenue in 2023, its fifth year of business. Oh, and it&#8217;s=
 </span><strong>EBITDA profitable</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">The $2.2 billion valuation seems hefty for a five-year-old compan=
y, but relative to the opportunity, it&#8217;s small. Companies that have c=
hewed off just the easier, surface-level piece of the problem &#8211; bette=
r interfaces on old infrastructure &#8211; like Broadridge and Interactive =
Brokers - are worth $24 billion and $41 billion in the public markets, resp=
ectively. Banks like Goldman, Morgan Stanley, Citi, JP Morgan, and Bank of =
America are worth, collectively, over $1 trillion.&#160;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">Clear Street believes that the banks are going to have a very difficult =
time modernizing their own systems while running them simultaneously and po=
tentially putting the trillions at risk. This isn&#8217;t just speculation:=
 Credit Suisse&#8217;s demise can be traced to poor risk management stemmin=
g from bad infrastructure.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The banks&#8217; reti=
cence is Clear Street&#8217;s opportunity: to rebuild the infrastructure fr=
om the outside, and replace the old system with the new, slowly at first, o=
ne client, geography, and asset at a time, until financial markets around t=
he world eventually run on Clear Street.&#160;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><=
span>Tackling that opportunity means building a startup in a different way =
than most startups build. This isn&#8217;t a story of minimum viable produc=
ts and pivots. Because it&#8217;s building infrastructure, Clear Street loo=
ks more like the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/70160141-c=
3e2-415f-a205-e969b1e2a5b0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: u=
nderline;">Techno-Industrials</a><span> that operate against a clear roadma=
p, with higher capital requirements and more specialized talent, from day o=
ne, than like a traditional software company.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>Clear Street&#8217;s cofounder, </span><strong>Uri Cohen</strong=
><span>, started the business with his own capital in 2018 after experienci=
ng the pain, and worrying about the </span><strong>risk</strong><span> of t=
rading on crumbling infrastructure for over two decades on Wall Street. He =
recruited a CEO, Chris Pento, and a CTO, Sachin Kumar to co-found the compa=
ny, both of whom had felt the same pain.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
<span>Then, in 2020, they bought their own online brokerage, CenterPoint Se=
curities, to serve as the first customer of Clear Street&#8217;s clearing, =
custody, and prime brokerage products. If they were going to ask financial =
institutions to move off of their old, but tried and true, infrastructure, =
they&#8217;d need to prove that it worked on themselves, a la </span><a hre=
f=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/815c8ac1-e827-4271-bd66-1ae6ddeff0ec?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Amazon&#8217;s fi=
rst and best customer strategy</a><span>.&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;"><span>Meanwhile, they got to work completely </span><strong>rebuildi=
ng financial infrastructure from the ground up</strong><span> with modern s=
oftware that needs to communicate with antiquated systems, like DTCC, and a=
 hodgepodge of customers&#8217; bespoke patchworks of code. They also began=
 building all of the things that a </span><strong>prime brokerage</strong><=
span> needs to do to win clients&#8217; business: research, investment bank=
ing, capital introductions, securities lending, margin, and more all at the=
 same time.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Clear Street, while still ear=
ly in its journey, is executing on its mission to build the cloud native pi=
pes through which the capital markets will one day run, across every major =
asset class, in every major market, replacing the antiquated system that ev=
eryone from small prime brokerages to large banks use to move trillions of =
dollars every day.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>And they&#8217;re offer=
ing a diverse product set that takes advantage of this modern technology st=
ack, giving the largest hedge funds that currently work with banks, down to=
 the smallest day traders that the bank can&#8217;t touch due to their cost=
 structure, </span><strong>clean data from one single source of truth</stro=
ng><span>, bringing crystal clarity into their risk, and driving operationa=
l and strategic efficiencies in their businesses that could lead to growth =
that they can only currently dream of.&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">The ambition seems unlimited, because practically, it is. &#8220;The ma=
rkets&#8221; are the world&#8217;s largest market.&#160;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>The </span><em>risk</em><span> of capital market participants not =
modernizing their infrastructure, product offerings, and services, Uri beli=
eves, is equally huge: a Boeingesque series of increasingly frequent blowup=
s like the ones that killed Archegos Capital Management, Credit Suisse, and=
 Signature Bank, and worse.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There are a c=
ouple of ways they might come to appreciate the risk: the threat and the op=
portunity.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The threat is the risk of catastrophe=
 that comes from operating on old infrastructure, the risk that Credit Suis=
se and Signature Bank learned the hard way but that takes at least a decade=
 to remedy, at which point it&#8217;s someone else&#8217;s problem (or glor=
y).&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The opportunity is the set of possibilities =
that opens up when you can build products on one cloud-based platform with =
clean, real-time data. Every bank C-suite is thinking through how to take a=
dvantage of AI, for example, which could be catastrophic with bad data but =
nirvanic with good data.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In either case, the ban=
king industry has proven that words aren&#8217;t as powerful as incentives.=
 The industry&#8217;s current leaders don&#8217;t want to wade through the =
quagmire of replacing infrastructure, so Clear Street needs to build new in=
frastructure in parallel so that adopting it is a no-brainer for the indust=
ry&#8217;s future leaders.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget"=
 style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: ant=
ialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: a=
ntialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-fa=
mily: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, '=
Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Sego=
e UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line=
-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Thin=
king in Risk</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Clear Street was born from a li=
fetime of experience and one specific conversation.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">Uri has spent over two decades in the financial markets. He&#8217;s a c=
o-founder of Alpine Global Management, a firm with a breadth of sophisticat=
ed trading strategies across global markets, the kind of firm that demands =
a lot from its infrastructure.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>A few years=
 ago, Alpine had an issue with one of its large </span><strong>prime broker=
s</strong><span>, the one-stop-shops investment banks and financial institu=
tions offer to support large investors. Prime brokers offer margin, securit=
ies lending, custody, trade clearing and settlement, risk management, repor=
ting and more. But this large prime&#8217;s risk management and reporting w=
ere broken.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Their system was cobbled toge=
ther from a string of acquisitions, and it was giving Uri the wrong data an=
d costing him money. They miscalculated how much equity he had, against whi=
ch they provided margin, and as a result, the fees he was paying were wrong=
=2E&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=20=
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">He needed it fixed, but there was a problem: t=
he only guy who knew how to fix it was a retired 70-year-old named Neil Ste=
panich who happened to be vacationing in the Himalayas.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Uri somehow got in touch with Neil, who said that he could fix it=
, &#8220;but it&#8217;s going to cost you a lot of money: $2,000.&#8221; Th=
at was just fine. Two hours later, it was fixed, temporarily, at least.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Over the next few years, Uri kept having more and m=
ore issues with the systems his prime brokers provided. He kept thinking, &=
#8220;OK, the banks will have to fix it now,&#8221; and the banks kept not =
fixing it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Five years later, things had only got=
ten worse.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That year, in a meeting with two head=
s of prime brokerages, he asked, &#8220;Why aren&#8217;t you guys fixing th=
is?&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The answer was simple and human: &#82=
20;It&#8217;s going to take seven to ten years, a lot of money, and a lot o=
f headaches. We&#8217;re not even sure we will succeed.&#8221;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">From their perspective, the decision not to fix makes sense: the =
payoff was too far out and uncertain. From Uri&#8217;s, it didn&#8217;t wor=
k: the system was causing him to lose money.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, =
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">During th=
at conversation, Uri made the realization that many entrepreneurs make at s=
ome point: if he wanted the system fixed, he was going to have to fix it hi=
mself.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appea=
rance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-ap=
pearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearan=
ce: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Di=
splay', -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, H=
elvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe =
UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; mar=
gin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Why Clear Street is So H=
ard to Build</strong><br></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">What Uri, Chris Pento, and =
Sachin Kumar set out to build in 2018, on the surface, doesn&#8217;t sound =
too dissimilar from many software startups.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>Clear Street was going to take an antiquated system and modernize it with=
 software. Instead of mainframes, Clear Street would be cloud native. Inste=
ad of clunky integrations, Clear Street would be </span><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/1563b853-fc53-4be6-9ce7-dce7d0c25ef8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">API-first</a><span>. In place of=
 slow, duct-taped systems and manual spreadsheets, Clear Street would give =
clients a comprehensive view of their portfolios in real-time and the abili=
ty to execute trades at internet speed.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A=
nd that is what they&#8217;re building. Clear Street offers clearing and cu=
stody, execution, prime financing, and white-glove services like capital in=
troductions and account management to financial institutions and active tra=
ders.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Executing the startup playbook on th=
e world&#8217;s financial infrastructure, though, is hard. Clear Street is =
a </span><strong>Hard Startup</strong><span>. In </span><em><a href=3D"http=
s://substack.com/redirect/c4c4dc66-5d33-4bd0-b7c8-c250a7224880?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color:=
 rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">The Good Thing About Hard Th=
ings</a></em><span>, I defined Hard Startups as:</span></p><blockquote styl=
e=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>The ones with no playbook, the ones that h=
ave R&amp;D risk or some other hair on them that keeps competition at bay a=
nd gives them a clear path to short-term sales and long-term defensibility =
if they get a great product to market.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>I broke them down to bits and atoms, and included </span><strong>i=
nfrastructure</strong><span> in the bits category: &#8220;these companies a=
re often 100x harder below the surface than above it; there&#8217;s a lot o=
f schlep.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Clear Street is perhaps the be=
st example of a bits infrastructure Hard Startup I&#8217;ve come across. Re=
building the world&#8217;s financial infrastructure has more hair on it tha=
n Sasquatch.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The software challenge is incredibl=
y hairy in its own right, and software is only one part of the story. Clear=
 Street needs capital, risk management, and the client services muscle of a=
n investment bank in order to get big clients to even use the software in t=
he first place.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Let&#8217;s start with the softw=
are. It&#8217;s the core of the business and the thing that makes Clear Str=
eet different from other prime brokerages.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4de9ca5b-3c63-4b63-8f82-5ec5b15c1a9e?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Jon Daplyn</a><sp=
an>, the former Head of Prime Brokerage Technology at Morgan Stanley and no=
w Clear Street&#8217;s Chief Information Officer, explained the challenge.&=
#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>&#8220;The hardest thing,&#8221; he=
 told me, &#8220;is that </span><strong>the systems you&#8217;re interactin=
g with were built decades and decades ago</strong><span>. No one is </span>=
<em>building</em><span> them; they were built in the past. You&#8217;ve eff=
ectively got to go and learn them from scratch.&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">He described a steep learning curve and a ton of tech that ne=
eded to be built in order to put in even the first trade.</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">To start, you need to build your own core books and records that keep t=
rack of client information, account balances and positions, cost basis, mar=
gin details, and more, a big database of client information that updates in=
 real-time. A database sounds relatively straightforward, but with so much =
information, from a variety of sources, including up-to-date market data, i=
t&#8217;s a beast.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>When I asked Jon for an=
 example of something that was particularly hard to build, he cited this &#=
8220;</span><strong>account master</strong><span>,&#8221; the core system t=
hat maintains all client information and positions.&#160;</span></p><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">&#8220;You&#8217;d think implementing an account master would be=
 straightforward,&#8221; he said, &#8220;but we&#8217;re already rolling ou=
t the second version because we didn&#8217;t get it quite right the first t=
ime.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">He noted, though, that this is the a=
dvantage of being a fintech instead of a bank: instead of saying &#8220;Why=
 did you make that mistake?&#8221; they looked at it and said, &#8220;That =
didn&#8217;t work, let&#8217;s rip it up and do it again.&#8221;&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;Our core value is technology, so we need it to be e=
xcellent.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Step one is building excellent =
technology internally &#8211; that single source of truth that provides cle=
an data to Clear Street and its clients. From there, Clear Street needs to =
connect its own systems with a patchwork of external ones that have no will=
ingness to change the way they work to speak with a new entrant.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">To enable even the first trade, Clear Street&#8217;s syste=
ms need to communicate with an alphabet soup of organizations, each of whic=
h have their own antiquated and mission-critical systems, like DTCC (Deposi=
tory Trust &amp; Clearing Corporation) and ICE (Intercontinental Exchange).=
 The DTCC is responsible for clearing US securities, but individual exchang=
es, like NASDAQ, have their own clearing processes and systems that occur a=
longside the DTCC&#8217;s centralized clearing.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(6=
4, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Just t=
aking NASDAQ, trading activity on that exchange generates data that needs t=
o flow through to post-trade systems for proper clearing and settlement. Th=
at includes obvious things like trade details &#8211; how many shares, what=
 price, etc&#8230; &#8211; and less obvious things, like accounting for the=
 exchange&#8217;s fees. Then there are the periodic things that happen &#82=
11; like stock splits, dividends, and repurchases &#8211; that happen at th=
e exchange level and must get reflected properly in Clear Street&#8217;s ow=
n systems.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s just one exchange! Clear=
 Street needs to send data to NASDAQ, other exchanges, clearinghouses, and =
regulators in formats in which they can digest it, and take data back in wh=
ichever format they choose to send it, clean it all up, and show it accurat=
ely in its own internal systems in order to give clients a real-time unders=
tanding of their positions, and in order to give Clear Street itself the da=
ta it needs to do things like extend margin to clients without blowing itse=
lf up.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">And then, it needs to share that data wit=
h clients in a format that works for them. Many hedge funds and brokerages =
have built their own patchwork of systems and ways of handling data on top =
of old infrastructure, and since they&#8217;re not going to rip everything =
out and replace it with Clear Street whole cloth on day one, Clear Street n=
eeds to translate the data in its own system into language that each of tho=
se systems understands. It&#8217;s like a real-time Rosetta Stone operating=
 inside of the chaos of the Tower of Babel.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">And =
that&#8217;s just US equities!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Then, with the co=
re systems built, Clear Street has to scale all of that &#8211; to more cli=
ents, more assets, and more geographies, each with its own idiosyncrasies a=
nd old systems with which to integrate.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=
 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Le=
t&#8217;s say they wanted to support bonds, or &#8220;fixed income,&#8221; =
in the US. They&#8217;d have to integrate with the DTCC&#8217;s FICC system=
 (Fixed Income Clearing Corporation), Fedwire, TradeWeb, and the fixed inco=
me exchanges, among other systems. Internally, they&#8217;d need to update =
their systems to account for securities that don&#8217;t trade like equitie=
s and come with their own valuation math. I still get nightmares from readi=
ng Frank Fabozzi&#8217;s </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
t/2dddd153-b440-4abd-85e5-70f6812fd93f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-d=
ecoration: underline;">The Handbook of Fixed Income Securities</a></em><spa=
n> early in my career. Clear Street essentially has to incorporate the bond=
 math from that 1840 page tome into its internal systems in order to proper=
ly account for risk.&#160;</span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-containe=
r-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">=
<figure style=3D"margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;"><table class=3D"image-wrappe=
