ght: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative=
;"><strong>COBOL Cowgirl and Cowboys</strong></h4><p style=3D"color: rgb(64=
, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Even th=
e people betting their career on replacing COBOL are in awe of it.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">When I asked what he thought about the language, Jon Dap=
lyn warned me that he was about to recite me a love letter to COBOL.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;If you think about it,&#8221; he said, &#8220;S=
omeone wrote a piece of software decades ago that&#8217;s still working tod=
ay. That&#8217;s remarkable.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">COBOL is tru=
ly remarkable.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In the 1940s and 1950s, computer =
scientists had to speak the language of machines, which they did at first b=
y setting switches and plugging and unplugging cables&#8230;&#160;</p><div =
