 underline;">Yes.</a><span> But it seems to be true. COBOL programs are as =
Lindy as computer programs get.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, =
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But there=
 are a couple of challenges with continuing to rely on COBOL.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">The first is a straightforward one: we&#8217;ve developed muc=
h better ways to write and run software. No one starting from scratch build=
s on COBOL.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The second is the bigger risk: the p=
eople who know how to work with COBOL are leaving the workforce.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>When I wrote about </span><a href=3D"https://substac=
